### 2.2. Author a fractured cube in memory

**Step A – Build a triangle mesh for a unit cube**

Use the helper `NvBlastExtAuthoringCreateMeshOnlyTriangles(vertices, vertexCount, indices, indexCount)`. It only needs positions and indexed triangles. (Materials are optional.) ([NVIDIA Omniverse][4])

```cpp
using namespace Nv::Blast;

// 8 cube vertices at corners of a unit cube centered at origin
static const float V[] = {
    -0.5f,-0.5f,-0.5f,   +0.5f,-0.5f,-0.5f,
    +0.5f,+0.5f,-0.5f,   -0.5f,+0.5f,-0.5f,
    -0.5f,-0.5f,+0.5f,   +0.5f,-0.5f,+0.5f,
    +0.5f,+0.5f,+0.5f,   -0.5f,+0.5f,+0.5f
};
static const uint32_t I[] = {
    // 12 triangles (two per face), CCW
    0,1,2,  0,2,3,   // -Z
    4,6,5,  4,7,6,   // +Z
    0,4,5,  0,5,1,   // -Y
    3,2,6,  3,6,7,   // +Y
    0,3,7,  0,7,4,   // -X
    1,5,6,  1,6,2    // +X
};

Mesh* srcMesh = NvBlastExtAuthoringCreateMeshOnlyTriangles(
    V, 8, const_cast<uint32_t*>(I), 36 /* 12 tris * 3 */
);
```

**Step B – Fracture it with Voronoi**

Create a `FractureTool`, feed it the mesh, generate site points, and call `voronoiFracturing`. Then finalize to bake the internal split geometry. (Note: for the *root* chunk (ID 0) you should *not* use `replaceChunk=true` – the API considers that invalid for the root; generate children at the next depth.) The functions and behavior are in the FractureTool docs. ([NVIDIA Omniverse][5])

```cpp
FractureTool* ft = NvBlastExtAuthoringCreateFractureTool();

// Give it the source mesh
Mesh* meshes[] = { srcMesh };
ft->setSourceMeshes(meshes, 1, nullptr);

// Make N random Voronoi sites inside the unit cube
std::vector<NvcVec3> sites;
const uint32_t cellCount = 32;  // tweak for coarser/finer pieces
sites.reserve(cellCount);
for (uint32_t i = 0; i < cellCount; ++i) {
    float x = -0.5f + static_cast<float>(rand())/RAND_MAX;  // [-0.5, 0.5]
    float y = -0.5f + static_cast<float>(rand())/RAND_MAX;
    float z = -0.5f + static_cast<float>(rand())/RAND_MAX;
    sites.push_back({x,y,z});
}

// Fracture root chunk (id 0); put new chunks at next depth (replaceChunk=false)
ft->voronoiFracturing(/*chunkId=*/0, cellCount, sites.data(), /*replaceChunk=*/false);

// Bake results into final chunk geometry
ft->finalizeFracturing();
```

**Step C – Turn fracture results into a Blast asset (chunks+bonds)**

Run the **BondGenerator** to compute bonds between neighboring support chunks and assemble **chunk/bond descriptors**. You can call the path optimized for `FractureTool` output; or use the higher-level helper `NvBlastExtAuthoringProcessFracture` to build the `AuthoringResult` in one go (includes `NvBlastAsset* asset`, optional render/collision hulls). See the authoring docs for these functions and the `AuthoringResult` fields. ([NVIDIA Omniverse][6])

```cpp
// (A) “Do‑it‑for‑me” path: one call prepares the asset & geometry
ConvexDecompositionParams hullParams{};     // defaults are fine to start
// You need a ConvexMeshBuilder implementation; in most setups it’s created by your
// integration layer. If you don’t have one yet, you can skip collision building for now
// and just create the asset (physics can be added later).

BlastBondGenerator* bondGen = NvBlastExtAuthoringCreateBondGenerator(/*ConvexMeshBuilder*/ nullptr);

// Mark all bottom-level generated chunks as “support”.
// A typical choice: support = depth == maxDepth (leaf chunks).
std::vector<bool> isSupport;
isSupport.resize(ft->getChunkCount(), true);  // start simple: all leaves are support

std::vector<NvBlastBondDesc> bonds;
std::vector<NvBlastChunkDesc> chunks;
bondGen->buildDescFromInternalFracture(ft, isSupport, bonds, chunks);  // authoring docs show this signature

// Now cook a low-level asset from descriptors.
NvBlastAssetDesc llDesc{};
llDesc.chunkCount = static_cast<uint32_t>(chunks.size());
llDesc.chunkDescs = chunks.data();
llDesc.bondCount  = static_cast<uint32_t>(bonds.size());
llDesc.bondDescs  = bonds.data();

void* mem = NVBLAST_ALLOC(NvBlastGetAssetMemorySize(&llDesc));
NvBlastLog logFn = nullptr;  // or provide a logging callback
NvBlastAsset* llAsset = NvBlastCreateAsset(mem, &llDesc, logFn);
```

> Tip: Instead of the manual `buildDescFromInternalFracture` + `NvBlastCreateAsset`, you can use `NvBlastExtAuthoringProcessFracture` to fill an `AuthoringResult` which already contains `asset`, bonds/chunks, render geometry and collision hulls – handy once you want physics shapes. See the function list in **NvBlastExtAuthoring.h** and the `AuthoringResult` struct (contains `NvBlastAsset* asset`, `collisionHull`, `geometry`, offsets, etc.). ([NVIDIA Omniverse][3])

**Step D – Wrap the low‑level asset in the high‑level Tk layer**

The Tk layer makes life easier (family, events, groups). Create a `TkFramework`, then a `TkAsset` from the low‑level asset, and finally a `TkActor` (that automatically creates a `TkFamily`). This flow is shown in the Tk user guide (“Creating a TkAsset” and “Instancing a TkAsset”). ([NVIDIA Omniverse][1])

```cpp
using namespace Nv::Blast;

TkFramework* framework = NvBlastTkFrameworkCreate();

TkAsset* tkAsset = framework->createAsset(llAsset /*takes ownership?*/, nullptr, 0, true);

TkActorDesc actorDesc{};
actorDesc.asset = tkAsset;
TkActor* tkActor = framework->createActor(actorDesc);

// Family holds all current and future child actors
TkFamily& family = tkActor->getFamily();
```

