### 2.3. Create and configure the **Stress Solver** for this family

The Stress Solver operates on the **low‑level family** (`NvBlastFamily`) and the asset’s **support graph**. You create it once, provide node info (mass/volume/position), then on each frame you apply forces/accelerations and call `update()`. If bonds are overstressed, ask it for **fracture commands** and **apply** them to the family. All of this – including method names and sequence – is in the class reference and the extension overview. ([NVIDIA Omniverse][2])

```cpp
// Access the low-level family (needed by ExtStressSolver::create)
const NvBlastFamily* llFamily = family.getFamilyLL();  // TkFamily API
ExtStressSolver* stress = ExtStressSolver::create(*llFamily);

// Fill node info (mass/volume/centroid) from LL asset automatically using a density
stress->setAllNodesInfoFromLL(/*density=*/1000.0f);  // kg/m^3, e.g. wood-ish density
// (Doc: uses chunk volumes & centroids; nodes marked ‘external’ are treated as static.) :contentReference[oaicite:12]{index=12}

// Configure bond limits (elastic and fatal thresholds, in Pascals)
ExtStressSolverSettings s{};
s.maxSolverIterationsPerFrame = 64;  // upper bound per frame
s.compressionElasticLimit = 1.0e5f;
s.compressionFatalLimit   = 5.0e5f;
s.shearElasticLimit       = -1.0f;   // negative = fall back to compression limits
s.shearFatalLimit         = -1.0f;
s.tensionElasticLimit     = -1.0f;
s.tensionFatalLimit       = -1.0f;
stress->setSettings(s);  // can be adjusted at runtime :contentReference[oaicite:13]{index=13}

// Register the initial actor with the solver
stress->notifyActorCreated(*tkActor->getActorLL());   // TkActor exposes getActorLL() :contentReference[oaicite:14]{index=14}
```

