### 2.4. Per‑frame loop: apply forces → update solver → fracture if needed

Here is a minimal loop that:

* Applies a force at a point on the actor (e.g., from a “bullet hit”),
* Updates the solver, and if bonds are overstressed,
* Generates fracture commands and applies them to the family (which dispatches split events).

The relevant methods are `addForce`, `update`, `getOverstressedBondCount`, `generateFractureCommands`, and `TkFamily::applyFracture`. ([NVIDIA Omniverse][2])

```cpp
void applyLocalImpact(ExtStressSolver& stress, TkActor& tkActor,
                      const NvcVec3& localHitPos, const NvcVec3& localForce)
{
    // Apply a force/impulse to the nearest graph node of this actor
    stress.addForce(*tkActor.getActorLL(), localHitPos, localForce /*, ExtForceMode::FORCE*/);
}

void tickDestruction(ExtStressSolver& stress, TkFamily& family)
{
    // 1) Solve bond stresses with all forces applied this frame
    stress.update();

    // 2) If any bonds are overstressed, generate fracture commands and apply them
    if (stress.getOverstressedBondCount() > 0) {
        // For simplicity we’ll process the single actor case:
        // In general, prefer generateFractureCommandsPerActor.
        // (We need the low-level actor pointer.)
        // tkActor reference available? Use family.getActors(...) to iterate.

        // Collect current actors from the family
        std::vector<TkActor*> actors(family.getActorCount());
        family.getActors(actors.data(), static_cast<uint32_t>(actors.size()));

        std::vector<NvBlastFractureBuffers> cmds(actors.size());
        std::vector<const NvBlastActor*> llActors; llActors.reserve(actors.size());

        uint32_t n = 0;
        for (TkActor* a : actors) {
            if (!a) continue;
            llActors.push_back(a->getActorLL());
            stress.generateFractureCommands(*a->getActorLL(), cmds[n++]);
        }

        // Apply to the whole family (Blast will split actors and dispatch events)
        for (uint32_t i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            family.applyFracture(&cmds[i]);  // TkFamily::applyFracture
        }
    }
}
```

> **Important:** When actors split, you must notify the stress solver about the new/destroyed low‑level actors. Call `notifyActorDestroyed` for the old one(s) and `notifyActorCreated` for each child. Typically you do this in your **TkFamily event listener** when you handle split events. The Stress Solver class docs call this out explicitly. ([NVIDIA Omniverse][2])

